Long-horn Miao, or Qing Miao, is a branch of Miao ethnic minority group, which is considered as the most mysterious and isolated group living in the depths of mountain forest in western part of the province. This small community has only 5,000 people worldwide, living in 12 tribes in Liuzhi and Zhijin counties today. They do not have a written language, but use bamboo carvings as chronicles. For many years, they have been reserving ancient culture and costumes, and the most unique and primary one is huge horn-shaped headdress, which is made by wrapping their ancestors hair around a large horn-shaped comb. #ethicminority #ruralchina #chinatoday #Guizhou @eyesonchinaproject #onassignment

#onassignment Weak #Russian demand hits Chinese border town businesses:At #manzhouli, Ding, originally from East Chinas Shandong Province, has been selling sweats and hats for nine years to Russian customers, with the help of his wife who is fluent in Russian, but things are getting tougher as less Russians come to buy his products.
Just three years ago, Russian customers used to purchase 10,000 yuan worth of products during one trip, but now they only spend 100 yuan, Ding said, noting that his store now makes only about 3,000 to 4,000 yuan a month, which can barely support his family.   @eyesonchinaproject

Mr Feng is in charge of this railway station in #Yiwu, which is also the starting point for the cross border cargo line called Yixinou. Over 13000 kilometers rail line is the longest in the world, passing through countries like Russia, Poland, and Germany. It connects two largest wholesale markets in the world, Yiwu in east China and Madrid, capital of Spain. node.text: Due to the #censorship in China, this story about laid off coal workers in #Hegang city in Northeast China's Heilongjiang Province was killed by the editorial team who is facing the pressure from the government. Yes, it's time to quit. #chinadictatorship #nofreedom #coal

Mr. Ma lives in Hegang, Northeast China's Heilongjiang Province. The region has been famous for coal production for decades. However, due to the downward pressure on the commodity market, many coal producers went bankrupt, and workers have not been paid for months. Mr. Ma was showing me an empty coal factory, which has been "temporarily" shutdown due to the high debt issue. #chinaeconomy #coal #overcapacity @eyesonchinaproject

Dongguan, city in South China's Guangdong Province, is known as the world's factory, where many OEM and ODM locate. Today, it is hard to see in factories in Dongguan those scenes in the movies showing thousands workers busy at assembly lines, putting every part of a watch or a mobile phone shell together. Instead, hundreds of industrial robots scattered at different lines, adapted to the fast rhythm of production. #chinamanufacturing #worldfactory #onassignment

Coal workers in North China's Shanxi Province #Chinatoday #onassignment

In North China's Shanxi Province, one of the country's major coal-producing provinces, coal factories were shutdown because of the industry restructuring. Villages nearby were also abandoned because of large layoffs, which should be the showcase of China's real GDP growth. #onassignment #Chinatoday #chinaeconomy

Zhang Kai, 50, has been working at the Shuimowan Coal Mining Site for 10 years. But he has not been paid for more than 15 months. "No one protest here because we're all afraid of getting fired," he said. Those are the most vulnerable workers in this fast-developing country. They were all born in small villages and know little about workers rights. They can not easily get another job because coal mining is the only industry in this village located nearby Datong city, Northwest Shanxi Province. #chinaeconomy #Chinatoday #onassignment #coalindustry
